reviews:
['I was extremely dissatisfied with my staying on 19 to 24 October, 25. The attitude of the front desk staff named Hung. He was arrogant and condescending when talking to guests about the hotel‚Äôs policy. Although I explained that when booking through the app, it clearly stated that only a passport or ID was required, and I even showed him both documents, he insisted that without showing him a picture of my visa, I would not be allowed to check in ‚Äî and he did so with a very rude and bossy attitude.
Because of this, one of my family members had to leave an important meeting just to go back and take a picture of my visa for him, since I was too far away to do it myself. I had to wait for a long time to check in after a long flight, which was extremely inconvenient.
However, when I later saw the hotel‚Äôs policy posted in the room, it clearly DID NOT MENTION ANY REQUIREMENT TO PROVIDE A VISA (see photos attached), contrary to what he demanded. How dare he did that to me?

I strongly urge the hotel management to take action to correct this staff member‚Äôs unprofessional and disrespectful behavior. The hotel should also not arbitrarily change its policies without informing guests prior to booking.

The hotel itself lacked proper amenities ‚Äî the air conditioning was weak and did not cool the room sufficiently. Next to the hotel was an empty lot filled with trash, emitting a foul smell. This is something guests would never know until they arrive.
Please think carefully before booking this place. There are many other hotels nearby with similar prices but much better quality and service ‚Äî especially staff who know how to speak to guests professionally, unlike the receptionist at YoYo Hotel, the polluted environment and poor service attitude.', 'I booked this place in advance and the day we were supposed to check in, they claimed to have an electric outage and asked to switch us to their sister hotel instead. The place was also close to the airport so I thought nothing of it but once we came to the Yoyo Airport Hotel the quality of the room was so much lower than Yoko Hotel. The bathroom smelled moldy, the elevator doesn‚Äôt go up to our room so we had to carry our luggage up the stairs and most importantly the door lock wasn‚Äôt working. It didn‚Äôt feel safe to be there so I asked to cancel and they tried to switch us to another one called Red Sun Hotel which had an even lower rating. They said we can cancel on Agoda if we‚Äôd like but they won‚Äôt be returning our payment. This felt scammy but we knew there was nothing we could do so we just sucked it up for the night. I would never book this place again.', None]

reviews:
["I had a most comfortable stay here. I arrived shortly before 7 pm: the man and the lady working at reception even helped me carry my luggage up the stairs, to the reception. That was an amazing welcome. The man then accompanied me to the room and checked that the AC worked and that hot water was there. That was great.
The room was very comfy: the bed was good. Plus, there was a fridge and very comfortable chairs and a table. Cleaning is done by request, which suits me very well, because most times I don't need cleaning and prefer my room not to be entered. The staff speak a little English. To sum up, I would stay here again if I pass by Saigon again.

As to the downsides, I went out for dinner that same evening. When I came back and as I was waiting for the lift to arrive, I smelled a strong smell of cigarette smoke in the reception area. Having looked out, I saw that the late-evening/night receptionist was smoking in the reception area.
There is a also a big dark-coloured dog that sometimes comes to sit on the stairs, making it difficult to enter.
And yes, regarding the stairs: I'm young and capable, but I just think of elderly or disabled people: they will not be able to climb that flight of stairs. Meaning this hotel can't accommodate elderly or disabled people.
There was dust on the bedside lamp. And the shower holder was broken when I checked in: I had to hold the shower in my hand at all times when showering. I checked in shortly before 7 pm - I think that since the check-out of the previous guest, there was plenty of time to go to a plumbing shop and buy a new holder.

reviews: ['Easy to find location with tastefully decorated and exceptionally clean rooms. This place was so nice to come back to after a long, hot, humid day walking around town. I was happy to acquire the balcony I sought - even if it was pretty tiny. reviews:
['This 2-star hotel was a huge disappointment. First, the price was too expensive for what they offer. The service was poor, and there was no housekeeping during my stay. Worst of all, the bed had bugs/bed bugs! While the room looked clean at a glance, the facilities were extremely old and poorly maintained. The elevator was tiny and felt like it was about to break down at any moment. Avoid staying here if possible.', 'This stay was an absolute nightmare from start to finish. I struggle to understand how this establishment maintains its 2-star rating, as it falls short on every basic measure of hospitality and cleanliness.
The first major issue is the price. For a hotel of this caliber, the rates are shockingly expensive and offer zero value for money. You are paying a premium for facilities that are clearly ancient and desperately in need of renovation. The entire property feels dated and poorly maintained.
The problems continued inside the room, which was shockingly dirty. The lack of basic room service was frustrating, but the truly unacceptable issue was the sanitation. The room was not only visibly unclean, but I woke up with multiple bites, confirming my worst fears: the presence of bed bugs. This is a serious health hazard and indicates a profound failure in basic hygiene management.
In short, this hotel offers high prices, antiquated facilities, non-existent service, and an unsanitary environment. I strongly recommend prospective guests look elsewhere to avoid this miserable experience.', 'Ph√≤ng ·ªïn so v·ªõi t·∫ßm gi√°. OK

reviews: [None, "Stayed here overnight before transferring to another hotel. We arrived around midnight, wondering why we were dropped off near the marketplace. When we walked to the hotel, the lobby seemed to be closed and some staff were sleeping on the sofas. We had to ring the bell only to find out that the receptionist was sleeping under the reception desk. After paying a few dollars for a room good for 6 people (as long as four people don't mind being in one bed), we headed straight to our room. The corridors smelled like cigarette, but their rooms were clean enough. ||||They had a function hall, a spa, and some of my friends were saying there's a brothel hidden on the  uppermost floor too, but I'm not really sure. Some of their staff were friendly (at least the ones in the morning) and even recommended a good restaurant for us. We didn't eat within the hotel, but there are some noodle sellers outside that you ought to try if you're adventurous enough. Their noodles are pretty good for a very cheap price, but if you're too concerned about sanitation, eat somewhere else within the city centre.||||Our stay was bearable mostly because we weren't really into staying overnight in some fancy hotel and we were on a tight budget, so you really get what you pay for. But it's not a place I'd recommend for most people.", "The motel itself was not that bad. Average, I'd say. The grate was missing from the bathroom fan, and something was smeared on the wall in the bathroom. The bedroom was clean and surprisingly enough, there were English channels on the TV (Discovery, NatGeo, and CNN). We left to go on a tour early in the morning, and discovered the lobby was full of mopeds, and the desk clerk was asleep on the floor in the middle of them. Not very professional. Service people were polite and helpful when asked questions. You will catch some strange looks being a Caucasian in the area. Street vendors will try to get you to buy unnecessary junk as you exit the hotel. A friend of ours who lives there had his moped helmet stolen while he visited with us. Exercise extreme caution when arriving and exiting the building (pickpockets, etc.). If you want to stay close to the activity, this is not a bad choice.", 'This place actualy looked pretty good on the boking site. Imagine how disappointed we were on arrival. Set just back fom a mainn street in a dodgy area of town patrolled at night by mad dogs & large rats. The reception staff were very unhelpful, the hotel did not feel safe at all and our 3rd floor window looked out onto a part derelict and very old and unused concrete shopping mall or market. Breakfast was awful and we had to keep asking for anything tht resembled edible food!  The place was way overdue refurbishment (especialy the bathrooms) and we actually checked out a night early as we just did not enjoy our experience there. The attached Sauna (read brothel) was not a welcome addition to the hotel. My advice - AVOID!']

reviews:
['As soon as I entered the room, I was greeted with a strong cigarette smoke. I immediately asked to change to another room: the new room was somehow better, although it smelled of cigarette smoke throughout my stay as well (albeit less strong).
I think this hotel should invest in "addressable" cigarette smoke detectors: you place one in every room. Then, when an alarm is triggered, the security guard will see exactly in which room the guest is smoking and will be able to go to that room.

The AC was very dirty (see the picture attached). I lay in bed without the blanket, with the AC set to 16 degrees and maximum fan speed, but I was still sweating. It is high time they called an AC maintenance professional and had their AC cleaned and cooling gas refilled.

The environment is noisy: the biggest issue isn't even the road traffic but a nearby business playing music until 10 p.m.

Wi-Fi was weak and would almost disconnect (see the screenshot attached). Yet, I was using the Wi-Fi hotspot of my floor, not another floor. Watching a movie proved impossible: it would freeze all the time.

reviews: ["This time went I come to Vietnam, my friends recommended me GBS-Global Business Studio, a place very worth to try. Therefore, instead of booking hotel, I chose GBS. Although this apartment locates near the market (it's a chance to go around and experience Vietnamese life!), it's very quite, I can work all day without bothering. Love GBS, hope I'll have a chance to back there!", 'I used to live at GBS- Global Bussiness Studio 3 months when I come back  Viet Nam from France. reviews:
['The rooms are not clean, and there's this lingering unpleasant smell. Our shower had black mold in it, the drain was clogged, and the towels didn't really dry you. Honestly, I felt dirtier after my shower‚Äîwhich is super unpleasant after a long flight.

The hotel is in a super busy side street which makes it pretty hard and inconvenient to get to and out of.

The hotel markets itself as premium, but it just isn't; you can get a nicer place for much cheaper if you get away from the airport area a little bit.

A huge red flag that they don't show online is that they rent rooms by the hour and they offer a discount if you pay for two hours...so, that tells you who their primary clients are, because there're only so many reasons people would need a hotel room for only two hours üò≥. Which honestly explains the grimy feeling.

The staff are also flippant and patronizing. If you understand Vietnamese, you'll catch what I mean: lots of comments about how rich you must be and how much money you must have since you're staying at a "nice" hotel. It's quite uncomfortable riding the elevator with staff who won't stop talking about how rich you are, because you know..you're not, but they keep thinking you are. It gives you the ick. And! When I got to my room, it turns out staff were using it as their own room just seconds before.

If you like black mold, seedy neighbors, sewer smells, and eyes staring at you like you're walking an open purse/wallet, then this is the place for you. If you'd rather just relax, then go anywhere else. Anywhere at all.', 'D·∫°, t√¥i xin tr·∫£ l·ªùi r·∫±ng:

Value for Money: Considering the location, service, and the quality of the accommodations, Tito Homestay offers excellent value. Additional Perks: The rooftop area houses a washing machine. It's use was included.

In conclusion, my stay at Tito Homestay was memorable for all the right reasons. Whether you're a solo traveler, a couple, or a small group, this homestay provides a welcoming, comfortable base from which to explore this dynamic city. Haoran, Minh, Duy√™n', "It's good.‚ô°", 'Bij uitstek slechtste hotel waar we in 4 weken Vietnam geweest zijn. Bij aankomst moet je eerst wachten tot ze je roepen voor check in, heel raar. Ook niet erg vriendelijk..

De foto‚Äôs zien er anders uit dan in het echt. Het zwembad is mega klein, er staan 2 ligbedjes, dus je hebt sws geen plek. Ook zijn de randen behoorlijk groen van het vuil. Bovenin is het een rommelhoek.

Ontbijt was echt het slechts dat we in 4 weken Vietnam hadden. Alles was om half 9/9 al op, en ze wilden geen eitjes bij bakken omdat het ontbijt tot maar half 10 geserveerd wordt. Totaal onlogisch. Waren ook nul klantvriendelijk en zaten alleen maar op hun telefoon bezig.

3 sterren voor de kamer. De kamer was verder netjes, schoon. Maar klein. Ook hier deden de foto‚Äôs zich beter voor dan het was. Badkamer prima douche / bad. Lekkere waterstraal.

Ook zijn de kamers gehorig en hoor je de schoonmakers en ander personeel al vroeg. Ook hebben ze Walkie talkies dat door de gangen schettert.']

reviews:
["Our room at Nana's place (listed as Qu·∫≠n 3 - Economy Room on Airbnb) was probably the nicest accommodation we stayed in over our 3-week travels from South to North Vietnam.

The room has everything you could want from a small accommodation for two, plus a smart projector and pull-down screen for a little home cinema night! Nana and her co-hosts were all super-responsive and were quick and very courteous in helping us out with several minor issues we had over the course of our stay.

Most importantly, the place felt like a cozy retreat in a fairly central location in bustling Saigon, and we particularly loved the residential alley/close it was situated in. It can feel a little like a maze the first time you try to navigate your way there, but after that we really came to appreciate the homey vibes of the neighbourhood, and, with all local families and older-generation residents around, we felt, if anything, safer than being on a main street.

The best balance between a conveniently located private accommodation and a truly local experience!", 'I‚Äôve been here a month. Still have two months to go. I have zero complaints. The host respond very quickly and address all my concerns which are not many. The room is very comfy and everything works. They have indoor motorcycle parking if you rent a motorcycle like I have. I also park outside because the ramp is a little much for me.  The house it at the end of a dead end ally with no traffic and very little noise. It is very quiet.  There is a fourth floor terrace to relax on and I love the alley cats that guard the entrance.']
